---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import LessonGrid from '../../../../../components/LessonGrid.astro';
import LessonPage from '../../../../../components/LessonPage.astro';
import LessonSection from '../../../../../components/LessonSection.astro';
import TagList from '../../../../../components/TagList.astro';

const tinyPipeline = `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
var app = builder.Build();

app.Use(async (context, next) =>
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Before: {context.Request.Method} {context.Request.Path}");

    await next(context);

    Console.WriteLine($"After: {context.Response.StatusCode}");
});

app.MapGet("/status", () => Results.Ok(new
{
    Ok = true,
    CheckedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow
}));

app.Run();`;

const shortCircuit = `app.Use(async (context, next) =>
{
    if (context.Request.Path == "/blocked")
    {
        context.Response.StatusCode = 403;
        await context.Response.WriteAsync("Blocked");
        return;
    }

    await next(context);
});`;

const endpointHandler = `app.MapGet("/hello/{name}", (string name) =>
{
    return Results.Ok(new { Message = $"Hello, {name}" });
});`;
---

<LessonPage
  title="Lesson 2 · ASP.NET Core request pipeline"
  heading="The request pipeline: middleware before handlers"
  lede="Today’s win: understand what happens between an HTTP request arriving and your endpoint handler returning a response."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET lessons"
>
  <LessonSection title="The first-principles model">
    <Callout>
      A request does not jump straight to your handler. ASP.NET Core passes it through a pipeline: ordered steps that can inspect, modify, stop, or forward the request.
    </Callout>
    <p>
      Last lesson, you separated <strong>route</strong> from <strong>handler</strong>. Now add one layer before that: <strong>middleware</strong>.
      Middleware is code that runs on the way into the app, often before route handlers execute.
    </p>
    <TagList tags={['request arrives', 'middleware runs in order', 'endpoint handler matches', 'response travels back']} />
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Pipeline vs endpoint">
    <LessonGrid>
      <div>
        <h3>Middleware</h3>
        <p>
          Middleware is cross-cutting behavior. Think logging, auth, CORS, error handling, compression, and redirects.
        </p>
        <p>
          It usually does not care about one specific business route.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Endpoint handler</h3>
        <p>
          A handler is the route-specific worker. It answers one matched endpoint such as <code>GET /status</code> or <code>GET /users/42</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          It usually contains the action for that route.
        </p>
      </div>
    </LessonGrid>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="A tiny visible pipeline">
    <p>
      This example logs before and after the endpoint handler. The important line is <code>await next(context)</code>: it means “continue to the next step in the pipeline.”
    </p>
    <Code code={tinyPipeline} lang="csharp" />
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Middleware can short-circuit">
    <p>
      Middleware does not have to call <code>next</code>. If it returns early, later middleware and endpoint handlers do not run. That is called <strong>short-circuiting</strong>.
    </p>
    <Code code={shortCircuit} lang="csharp" />
    <p>
      This is why authorization, static files, redirects, and error handling care about pipeline order.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="The endpoint still does the route-specific work">
    <p>
      After the pipeline reaches endpoint routing, a matched route calls its handler. Parameters can be bound from the route, query string, body, services, and more.
    </p>
    <Code code={endpointHandler} lang="csharp" />
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Retrieval checkpoint — reply in Discord" variant="checkpoint">
    <p>Before the next lesson, answer these from memory:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>In one sentence, what is middleware?</li>
      <li>What does <code>await next(context)</code> mean?</li>
      <li>If middleware returns without calling <code>next</code>, what happens to the endpoint handler?</li>
    </ol>
  </LessonSection>
</LessonPage>
